"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-01-olympics-star-makes-disgusting-revelation-swimming-river-seine-21338462\", \"text\": \"An athlete who competed in the ParisOlympicstriathlon says she 'felt and saw things I do not want to think about' whileswimming in the River Seine.  Thepostponed triathlontook place on Wednesday after early morning tests showed the water quality in the Seine was finally at an acceptable level for the swim leg to go ahead.  But several competitors were still less than impressed by the pollution in the Seine, whichParisorganisers said had worsened after heavy rainfall over the weekend.  Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for latest news on the Olympics  Belgium's Jolien Vermeylen, who finished 24th in the women's event, said the water 'did not taste like Coke or Sprite' and admitted she was aware of the risk of getting sick.  'I drank a lot of water, so we will know tomorrow if I am sick or not,' she told TV channel VTM. 'It does not taste like\\u00a0Coca-Cola\\u00a0or Sprite, of course.  'While\\u00a0swimming\\u00a0under the bridge, I felt and saw things that we should not think about too much.  'The Seine has been dirty for a hundred years, so they can not say that the safety of the athletes is a priority. That's bulls***!'  Vermeylen took precautions to avoid getting sick but admits she took on quite a bit of water during the swim leg.  The 30-year-old added: 'If the race had not taken place, it would have been a disgrace for the organisation, for Paris, for France.  'It was now or never, and they could not cancel the race completely either. Now they just have to hope that there will not be too many sick athletes.  'I took pro-biotics, I drank my Yakult, I could not do more. I had the idea of \\u200b\\u200bnot drinking water, but yes, it failed.'  Following days ofconcerns over the River Seineand the triathlon events, two Team GB stars produced impressive performances to bag medals.  Tokyo 2020 silver medallist Alex Yee claimed gold in the men's event while Beth Potter battled to bronze in the women's race.  'I am so grateful to everyone who's been in my corner for the past three years. That was for them,' Yee told BBC Sport afterpassing New Zealand's Hayden Wilde late on.  'At 5km [on the run leg] I was going through a really bad patch and with 2.5km to go I thought \\\"I am going to give myself one last chance at this and not give up\\\", and here we are.'  Potter, meanwhile, said: 'I am so happy. I was going for the gold but Cassandre and Julie were just too good for me today and I am super happy to come away with the bronze.  'I have come a long way in eight years. I did it for me but I also did it for everyone who has helped me in eight years and believed in me from day one. It is for them back home as well.'  ArrowMORE:Turkish shooter who went viral explains why he does not need any equipment  ArrowMORE:Imane Khelif's next opponent issues warning ahead of Olympic boxing quarter final  ArrowMORE:The Simone Biles and MyKayla Skinner feud explained  Your guide to the week in football. Exclusive analysis, FPL tips and transfer talk - sign up, it's an open goal.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"